## Proposed Solution

### Option A: Remove max-width Entirely (Recommended)

**Change:**
```tsx
// Before (Layout.tsx:44)
<div className="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
  {children}
</div>

// After
<div className="w-full">
  {children}
</div>
```

**Pros:**
- Simple, one-line change
- Full viewport width on all screen sizes
- Consistent with modern web apps

**Cons:**
- Content might be too wide on ultra-wide displays (3440px+)
- No concerns for current target users (1920px-2560px)

### Option B: Larger Max Width with Breakpoints

**Change:**
```tsx
// After
<div className="w-full max-w-[2560px] mx-auto">
  {children}
</div>
```

**Pros:**
- Still uses full width up to 2560px
- Prevents content from being TOO wide on ultra-wide displays

**Cons:**
- Adds complexity
- May still constrain on some displays

### Decision: **Option A** (Remove max-width entirely)

**Rationale:**
- Simplest solution
- Matches user expectation ("full screen space available")
- If ultra-wide becomes an issue later, we can add breakpoints
- Most users on 1920px-2560px displays

